<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do you convert psi to bar?", answer: "To convert psi to bar, multiply the psi value by 0.0689476. For example, 100 psi equals approximately 6.895 bar. This works because 1 psi equals 6,894.76 pascals and 1 bar equals 100,000 pascals, so the conversion factor is 6894.76 / 100000 = 0.0689476." },
  { question: "What is the difference between bar and atm?", answer: "Bar and atmosphere (atm) are very close in value but not identical. One standard atmosphere equals exactly 101,325 pascals, while one bar equals exactly 100,000 pascals. Therefore, 1 atm is approximately 1.01325 bar. The bar is widely used in meteorology and engineering in Europe, while atm is more common in chemistry and American engineering contexts." },
  { question: "What is the standard atmospheric pressure?", answer: "Standard atmospheric pressure is defined as exactly 101,325 pascals (Pa), which equals 1 atmosphere (atm), approximately 1.01325 bar, 14.696 psi, 760 mmHg, or 760 Torr. This value represents the average air pressure at sea level and is used as a reference point in many scientific and engineering calculations." },
  { question: "Why are there so many pressure units?", answer: "Different pressure units evolved in different fields and regions. Pascal (Pa) is the SI standard used in physics. Bar is popular in European meteorology and industrial applications. PSI (pounds per square inch) is standard in American engineering. Atmospheres are traditional in chemistry. mmHg and Torr come from mercury barometer measurements and are used in medicine and vacuum technology. Each field tends to use the unit that gives convenient numbers for its typical pressure ranges." },
  { question: "How do you convert mmHg to atm?", answer: "To convert mmHg to atm, divide the mmHg value by 760. For example, 800 mmHg equals 800/760 = 1.053 atm. This is because the standard atmosphere is defined as the pressure exerted by a 760 mm column of mercury at 0 degrees Celsius under standard gravitational acceleration." }
]) %>

