      <h2>How the Pressure Converter Works</h2>
      <p><strong>Pressure</strong> is defined as force per unit area and is one of the most commonly measured physical quantities in science and engineering. This converter takes a pressure value in any supported unit, converts it to Pascal (the SI base unit of pressure) as an intermediate step, and then converts from Pascal to every other supported unit. This hub-and-spoke approach through a common reference unit ensures consistent, accurate conversions regardless of which source and target units you are working with.</p>

      <p>The tool supports ten widely used pressure units: <strong>Pascal (Pa)</strong>, <strong>kilopascal (kPa)</strong>, <strong>megapascal (MPa)</strong>, <strong>bar</strong>, <strong>PSI</strong> (pounds per square inch), <strong>atmosphere (atm)</strong>, <strong>millimeters of mercury (mmHg)</strong>, <strong>Torr</strong>, <strong>inches of mercury (inHg)</strong>, and <strong>kilogram-force per square centimeter (kgf/cm&sup2;)</strong>. Each has its own domain of common usage, from vacuum technology and medicine to automotive tire pressures and industrial hydraulics.</p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Common Pressure Unit Reference</h2>
      <p>Standard atmospheric pressure at sea level serves as a convenient reference point for comparing units:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>101,325 Pa</strong> (Pascal) &mdash; the SI definition of 1 standard atmosphere</li>
        <li><strong>101.325 kPa</strong> (kilopascal) &mdash; commonly used in weather forecasts outside the US</li>
        <li><strong>1.01325 bar</strong> &mdash; popular in European industry and meteorology</li>
        <li><strong>14.696 psi</strong> &mdash; standard in American engineering and tire pressure gauges</li>
        <li><strong>1 atm</strong> &mdash; the reference value used in chemistry (STP conditions)</li>
        <li><strong>760 mmHg / 760 Torr</strong> &mdash; traditional barometric measurement</li>
        <li><strong>29.921 inHg</strong> &mdash; used in US aviation and weather reporting</li>
        <li><strong>1.0332 kgf/cm&sup2;</strong> &mdash; traditional metric engineering unit</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>When to Use Each Unit</h3>
      <p>Choosing the right pressure unit depends on your field. Mechanical engineers working with hydraulic systems typically use bar or PSI. Medical professionals measure blood pressure in mmHg. Meteorologists in the United States report barometric pressure in inches of mercury (inHg), while those elsewhere use hectopascals (hPa, equivalent to millibars). Vacuum technologists often work in Torr or millibars. Scientists conducting experiments at standard conditions reference pressure in atmospheres or kilopascals. Understanding which unit your instruments and industry standards expect is essential for avoiding costly errors.</p>

      <h3>The Pascal as the SI Standard</h3>
      <p>The Pascal (Pa) is named after Blaise Pascal, the French mathematician and physicist who made pioneering contributions to the study of fluid pressure in the 17th century. One pascal equals one newton per square meter (1 Pa = 1 N/m&sup2;). Because a single pascal is a very small amount of pressure, kilopascals (kPa) and megapascals (MPa) are more commonly used in practice. For example, atmospheric pressure is about 101 kPa, and the yield strength of structural steel is typically around 250 MPa.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do you convert psi to bar?</h3>
      <p>To convert psi to bar, multiply the psi value by 0.0689476. For example, 100 psi equals approximately 6.895 bar.</p>

      <h3>What is the difference between bar and atm?</h3>
      <p>One standard atmosphere equals exactly 101,325 pascals, while one bar equals exactly 100,000 pascals. Therefore, 1 atm is approximately 1.01325 bar. They are close but not identical.</p>

      <h3>What is the standard atmospheric pressure?</h3>
      <p>Standard atmospheric pressure is defined as exactly 101,325 Pa, which equals 1 atm, approximately 1.01325 bar, 14.696 psi, or 760 mmHg.</p>

      <h3>Why are there so many pressure units?</h3>
      <p>Different pressure units evolved in different fields and regions. Pascal is the SI standard, bar is popular in Europe, PSI is standard in American engineering, and mmHg comes from mercury barometers used in medicine.</p>

      <h3>How do you convert mmHg to atm?</h3>
      <p>To convert mmHg to atm, divide the mmHg value by 760. For example, 800 mmHg equals 800/760 = 1.053 atm.</p>

